# [Explanatory Data Analysis]{style="font-size: 16px;"} {#sec-explanatory-data-analysis}

## [Logistic Regression]{style="font-size: 14px;"} {#sub-sec-log-reg}

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| eval: false

glimpse(obesity)
```

Logistic regression is used when the outcome of interest takes one of two categorical values (e.g. `Yes`/`No`). In this case, the response variable takes the value 1 (defined as success, with probability $p_i$) or 0 (defined as failure, with probability $1 - p_i$). And the response is given by $Y_i$ with Bernoulli distribution. The corresponding model uses the logit link function: $$
g(p_i) = 
\log\left(\frac{p_i}{1 - p_i}\right)
= \log\left(\frac{\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 1 \mid \underline{x}_i)}{\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 0 \mid \underline{x}_i)}\right)
= \underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta}
$$ {#eq-log-odds}

We can refer to @eq-log-odds as the log-odds, since $\frac{p_i}{1 - p_i}$ represents the odds. Taking the inverse of the logit link function gives the following: $$
\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 1 \mid \underline{x}_i)
= \frac{\exp(\underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta})}{1 + \exp(\underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta})}
$$ {#eq-odds-1} $$
\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 0 \mid \underline{x}_i)
= \frac{1}{1 + \exp(\underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta})}.
$$ {#eq-odds-0}

