# [Formal Data Analysis]{style="font-size: 16px;"} {#sec-formal-data-analysis}

## [Model Specification]{style="font-size: 14px;"} {#sub-sec-model-specification}

We will now fit a logistic model to investigate the relationship between obesity and explanatory variables. Let $Y_i = 1$ if individual *i* is obese and $Y_i = 0$ otherwise. We will assume that: $$Y_i \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p_i)$$where, $p_i = \mathbb{P}(Y_i = 1 \mid \underline{x}_i)$ and $Y_i = Obese_i$. The model is given by: $$logit(p_i)=\alpha_0 + \beta_1 \,\mathbb{I}_{(\text{Year}_i = 2014)}
+ \beta_2 \,\mathbb{I}_{(\text{Year}_i = 2015)}
+ \beta_3 \,\mathbb{I}_{(\text{Year}_i = 2016)}$$ {#eq-year-model}

where: 2013 is the reference year. The intercept $\alpha_0$ represents the log-odds of an individual being obese in the reference year 2013, and the coefficients $\beta_1$, $\beta_2$, $\beta_3$ represent the change in log-odds in each year compared to 2013.

To fit a logistic regression model, we will conduct variable selection using a backwards elimination approach, supported by model selection critera such as Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) and likelihood ratio test. The performance of the model we select will be assessed using the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve.

## [Results]{style="font-size: 14px;"} {#sub-sec-results}

#### Year vs prevalence

We will fit a logistic regression model using the logit link function, with `Obese` as the response and `Year` as the explanatory variable:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false 
#| label: tbl-yearmodel
#| tbl-cap: Coefficient of the logistic regression model
model_year <- glm(Obese ~ Year,
                  data = obesity,
                  family = binomial)

tab_model(model_year,transform=NULL)
```

The coefficients for all years appear close to zero. Additionally, the confidence intervals across all years include zero and p \> 0.05. This provides no evidence that year is a statistically significant predictor of obesity, which suggests that obesity prevalence has not changed over time. We can visualise the probabilities using the plot_model() function as follows:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false 
#| fig-width: 3
#| fig-height: 2
#| label: fig-log-odds
#| fig-cap: Coefficient of the Logistic Regression Model
theme_set(theme_minimal(base_size = 7))
plot_model(model_year, show.values = TRUE, transform = NULL, value.size = 2, 
           title = "Log-Odds", show.p = FALSE)
```

@fig-log-odds shows the estimated log-odds coefficients for each year relative to the reference category (2013) are all close to zero, and their confidence intervals include zero. This indicates that there is minimal difference in log-odds of obesity across years. Adding onto this, @tbl-yearmodel shows large p-values, which further provides evidence that year is not a statistically significant predictor of obesity. Comparing coefficients of the regression model with that of the reference level appears to be approximately the same. We can now obtain probability predictions for each year using the `predict()` function as follows:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| message: false
#| fig-width: 3
#| fig-height: 1.5
#| label: fig-prob-obesity
#| fig-cap: Prob. of Obesity by Year

nd <- tibble(Year = factor(c(2013, 2014, 2015, 2016),
                levels = levels(obesity$Year)))

p <- predict(model_year,
             newdata = nd,
             type = "link",
             se.fit = TRUE) |>
  as.data.frame() |>
  mutate(fit_prob = plogis(fit),
    ll = plogis(fit - 1.96 * se.fit),
    ul = plogis(fit + 1.96 * se.fit)) |>
  bind_cols(nd)

ggplot(p, aes(x = Year, y = fit_prob)) +
  geom_point(size = 0.8) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = ll, ymax = ul), width = 0.1) + theme(
  plot.title = element_text(size = 7),
  axis.title = element_text(size = 7),
  axis.text = element_text(size = 7)) +
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Prob. of obesity",
       title = "Predicted Probability of Obesity by Year") +
  ylim(0, 1)
```

From @fig-prob-obesity, we can predict the probability of obesity for each year. The probabilities appear to be constant at approximately 30%, with the confidence intervals overlapping. This, again, indicates that there is no significant change in obesity prevalence over time.

#### Comparison: Full Model vs. Reduced Model (with fruit intake removed)

We now investigate whether obesity differs by age, gender, socio-economic status, and lifestyle factors. By this, we will fit a full model including variables `Age`, `Sex`, `Education`, `Veg`, and `Fruit`. Our full model indicates that fruit intake is not a statistically significant predictor for obesity due to the large p-value (0.942) so it is removed. As seen in the reduced model, and to compare models we also fit a reduced model, with `Fruit` removed:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| label: tbl-modelcomp
#| tbl-cap: Model comparison

full_model <- glm(Obese ~ Age + Sex + Education + Veg + Fruit,
                   data = obesity,
                   family = binomial)

reduced_model<- glm(Obese ~ Age + Sex + Education + Veg,
                                 data = obesity,
                                 family = binomial)

tab_model(reduced_model, full_model, transform = NULL,
          dv.labels = c("Reduced Model", "Full Model"))

```

In summary, due to the insignificant p-value, we can remove fruit intake from the full model. The reduced model predictors are now all statistically significant. Next, we will compare the BIC of the reduced model again the full model to supplement this conclusion:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| label: tbl-bic
#| tbl-cap: Model BIC comparison

compare_performance(reduced_model,full_model,metrics = "BIC") %>% 
  kable()
```

The full model has a higher BIC in comparison to the reduced model, indicating a poorer balance between model fit and complexity. As a result, the reduced model is preferred. In addition to this, we can conduct a likelihood ratio test:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| label: tbl-anova
#| tbl-cap: Model likelihood ratio test
anova(reduced_model, full_model, test = "Chisq") %>% 
  kable()

```

A likelihood ratio test comparing the reduced and full models yields a p-value of 0.94. Since this is greater than 0.05, there is no evidence that the additional predictor, fruit intake, improve model fit.

#### Model check

We will now investigate diagnostic plots to assess how well the model fits the data. This way we can assess whether our assumptions are met:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 10
#| fig-height: 2.6
#| label: tbl-pp-bin
#| fig-cap: Posterior predictive check and binned residuals for the reduced model
theme_update(
  text = element_text(size = 5),
  plot.title = element_text(size = 5),
  axis.title = element_text(size = 5),
  axis.text = element_text(size = 4),
  strip.text = element_text(size = 5),
  legend.text = element_text(size = 5)
)
check_model(
  reduced_model,
  check = c("pp_check", "binned_residuals")) 
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 10
#| fig-height: 2.4
#| label: tbl-outlier-qq
#| fig-cap: Influential observations and quantile residuals for the reduced model
theme_update(
  text = element_text(size = 5),
  plot.title = element_text(size = 5),
  axis.title = element_text(size = 5),
  axis.text = element_text(size = 5),
  strip.text = element_text(size = 5),
  legend.text = element_text(size = 5)
)
check_model(
  reduced_model,
  check = c("outliers", "qq")) 
```

The posterior predictive check (top-left) shows that most residuals lie within the expected error bounds, with no strong systematic pattern. This suggests there is no systematic discrepancies between real and simulated data. The binned residual plot (top-right) shows that most of the residuals lie within the expected error bounds, with about 95% of the residuals to fall inside the error bounds. The influential observations plot (bottom-left) indicates that all points on this plot lie within Cook's distance. Therefore, there is no evidence of influential observations that affect the model. The uniformity of residuals (bottom-right) closely follows the theoretical line, suggesting that the model assumptions are appropriate and to which the observed values do not deviate from the model expectations using simulated residuals.

Finally, we will assess the performance of the model using the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| label: fig-roc
#| fig-width: 2
#| fig-height: 2
#| fig-cap: ROC Curve

pred_results <- obesity %>%
  mutate(.pred_1 = predict(reduced_model, type = "response"))

roc_curve(pred_results,
          truth = Obese,
          .pred_1,
          event_level = "second") %>%
  autoplot() + theme(
  plot.title = element_text(size = 7),
  axis.title = element_text(size = 7),
  axis.text = element_text(size = 7)) +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve",
       x = "1 - Specificity",
       y = "Sensitivity")
```

The ROC curve in @fig-roc indicates if the model was able to distinguish between obese and non-obese individuals. Since the curve appears to be close to the diagonal line, this indicates the model only performs slightly better than guessing at random. The area under the curve (AUC) is approximately 0.60, which suggests a moderate-poor predictive performance. This indicates that, although several predictors are statistically significant, the effect they have are not strong.

# [Discussion]{style="font-size: 16px;"} {#sec-discussion}

There is no significant evidence to suggest that obesity rates in the Scottish population change from 2013-2016. @tbl-yearmodel shows the proportions as relatively similar across years, and this is further evidenced by the logistic regression model used to predict obesity, as @fig-log-odds shows confidence intervals that include 0, meaning there is very little difference in the log-odds across the years. There are differences in obesity by age, gender, socio-economic status, or lifestyle factors. This is evidenced by @tbl-sex, @fig-age, @tbl-edu, @tbl-veg, as all of these show a difference in obesity prevalence within their own category. Furthermore, by being significant predictors of obesity in the logistic regression model - `Age`, `Sex`, `Education`, and `Veg` must have significant differences in obesity prevalence within their categories, otherwise they would not be significant predictors, like `Fruit`.

# [Conclusion]{style="font-size: 16px;"} {#sec-conclusion}

In conclusion, there is no suggested evidence that obesity prevalence has any significant chance over the years we considered in this report. Moreover, there was evidence of a difference in obesity by age, gender, socio-economic status, or vegetable consumption, however, no evidence of a difference was observed by fruit.

